'''John Drennan''' (born 13 November 1932, [[West Croydon, South Australia]]) is a former [[first-class cricket]]er for [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]]. He toured [[New Zealand]] and [[South Africa]] with the [[Australia cricket team|Australian team]] but did not play [[Test cricket]].

==Early career==
A tall fast-medium bowler, able to swing the ball either way,<ref name ="OCAC">''The Oxford Companion to Australian Cricket'', Oxford, Melbourne, 1996, pp. 148-49.</ref> Drennan made his first-class debut in the 1953-54 season, taking 17 wickets for South Australia in the [[Sheffield Shield]] at an average of 32.88.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/0/Sheffield_Shield_1953-54/South_Australia_Bowling.html South Australia Sheffield Shield bowling 1953-54]</ref> When the [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealanders]] played a match in Adelaide at the end of the season he took 5 for 83 in the New Zealanders' first innings of 459.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/21/21002.html South Australia v New Zealanders 1953-54]</ref>

He took 17 wickets at 24.23 in 1954-55,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/15/15959/f_Bowling_by_Season.html John Drennan bowling by season]</ref> including 5 for 58 and 4 for 42 against [[Queensland cricket team|Queensland]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/21/21384.html South Australia v Queensland 1954-55]</ref> Most significantly, he took four cheap wickets, all of major batsmen, in South Australia's narrow loss to the touring [[Marylebone Cricket Club|MCC]],<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/21/21344.html South Australia v MCC 1954-55]</ref> and was selected to open the bowling for an Australian XI against MCC in Melbourne a week later.

He took 6 for 82 against Queensland in 1955-56<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/21/21828.html South Australia v Queensland 1955-56]</ref> and played in a trial match that was held to help the national selectors choose the team for the tour of England in 1956.<ref>''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' 1957, pp. 869-70.</ref> He took four wickets in that match, and finished the season with 26 wickets at 26.96, as well as scoring 176 runs at 29.33,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/15/15959/f_Batting_by_Season.html John Drennan batting by season]</ref> but the last fast-bowling place in the touring side went to [[Pat Crawford]].

In 1956-57 Drennan took 23 wickets at 27.34, including his career-best figures of 6 for 69 against [[Victoria cricket team|Victoria]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/22/22296.html Victoria v South Australia 1956-57]</ref>

==Playing for Australia==
After the 1956-57 Australian season, a young Australian team of 14 players [[Australian cricket team in New Zealand in 1956–57|toured New Zealand]], playing seven first-class matches, including three against the national team. Drennan was one of three fast bowlers, alongside [[Ian Meckiff]] and [[Ron Gaunt]]. He took wickets consistently in the provincial matches and played in the last two against New Zealand, finishing with 22 wickets at 12.50 in all six matches, though he took only two wickets against New Zealand.<ref>''Wisden'' 1958, pp. 846-52.</ref>

Drennan was selected for the [[Australian cricket team in South Africa in 1957–58|tour to South Africa in 1957-58]]. He took 5 for 53 against [[Rhodesia cricket team|Rhodesia]] in the first innings of the first match,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/22/22719.html Rhodesia v Australians, Salisbury 1957-58]</ref> and 5 for 43 and 2 for 33 in the innings victory over [[Border cricket team|Border]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/22/22735.html Border v Australians 1957-58]</ref> But in the second innings of the match against [[Eastern Province cricket team|Eastern Province]] shortly before the First Test, he broke down in his 11th over, tearing a [[hamstring]] muscle<ref name ="OCAC"/> after taking 3 for 25.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/22/22742.html Eastern Province v Australians 1957-58]</ref> He played in four of the remaining matches on tour but bowled little and took only one wicket.

==Later career==
He played two matches for South Australia in 1958-59 without taking a wicket. Thereafter, although he continued to play club cricket he played no more first-class matches. His first-class career ended just a few days after his 26th birthday.

In 1960 he played as the professional for [[Rishton Cricket Club|Rishton]] in the [[Lancashire League (cricket)|Lancashire League]], taking 81 wickets at 13.05 and scoring 430 runs at 19.55.<ref>''Wisden'' 1961, p. 735.</ref> He became a cricket coach.<ref name ="OCAC"/>

